What can you infer from these plots? Don’t just explain what’s in the graph, but speculate or tell a short story (1-2 paragraphs max).

TYPE YOUR ANSWER AFTER (AND OUTSIDE!) THIS BLOCKQUOTE.

The plots above display data gathered by the United Nation’s World Health Organization (WHO), which is a internationally renowned institution, and thus we deem the raw data as reliable. The plots above indicate that the country drinking the most beer per-capita in 2010 was Namibia, for spirits it was Grenada and for wine it was France. However, this is not necessarily indicative of the drinking habits of the populations of these countries per se, because, for example we need to take into account that some of this consumption will come from tourists. In particular, France is well-known worldwide for its wine production and hence tourists in the region will have contributed to the alcohol consumption reflected by the plot. Moreover, we need to take into consideration that the data points are per-capita and thus the chart has been distorted by the country’s population size. For instance, it seems surprising to see Grenada, a small island of the Caribbean, at the top of the plot for spirits, however this can be explained by their small population of only 110,000 people, which magnifies their drinking relatively high alcohol consumption. Similarly, it might be surprising that countries such as Russia and the US appear at the bottom of the plots, however, as these countries have large population size which offset their drinking habits. In addition, it might worth while to point out that countries such as the Czech Republic, Germany and Poland, which all have a reputation for their heavy alcohol consumption, unsurprisingly appear in the upper quartile of the rankings.

Notably, one-off events taking place in 2010 with high alcohol consumption associated to them could have also distorted these results. For instance, the 2010 World Cup took place in South Africa, potentially impacting the high alcohol consumption in neighboring Namibia. Similarly, countries such as Spain, the Netherlands, Brazil and Germany made it to the final stages of the tournament - and we speculate that the longer a country proceeds in such sporting events, the higher the beer consumption. Lastly, the limitations of the charts above must be noted. In fact, the data displayed dates back to 2010 and consequently it is fairly outdated and might not paint an accurate picture of the current alcohol consumption trends, which over 10 years could have changed dramatically.

ggplot(data=movies, mapping = aes(x = cast_facebook_likes, y = gross)) +

       x="Gross Earnings ($)") +
  theme_economist() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  scale_x_log10()

As facebook likes is the independent variable, we mapped this on the x-axis, and gross, which is speculated to be dependent on FB likes, this was mapped on the y-axis. In light of the plot above however, we can conclude that the number of facebook likes that the cast has received are not a good predictor of how much money a movie will make at the box office.

3 Returns of financial stocks

You may find useful the material on finance data sources.

We will use the tidyquant package to download historical data of stock prices, calculate returns, and examine the distribution of returns.

We must first identify which stocks we want to download data for, and for this we must know their ticker symbol; Apple is known as AAPL, Microsoft as MSFT, McDonald’s as MCD, etc. The file nyse.csv contains 508 stocks listed on the NYSE, their ticker symbol, name, the IPO (Initial Public Offering) year, and the sector and industry the company is in.

nyse <- read_csv(here::here("data","nyse.csv"))

Based on this dataset, create a table and a bar plot that shows the number of companies per sector, in descending order

# Creating df_comp that has companies per sector 
df_comp <- nyse %>%
  #Grouping companies by sector and using tally to count number of companies in each sector 
  group_by(sector) %>%
  tally()%>%
  #putting list in descending order 
  arrange(n)
#creating a bar chart 
ggplot(df_comp, aes(x= n , y = reorder(sector, n) )) + 
    geom_col() +
  #Adjusting chart and axes titles 
    ylab('Sector') +
    xlab('Number of Companies') +
    labs(title = 'Number of Companies per sector') +
  #Changing theme
    theme_economist() +
  #removing the gap between y axis and the start of bar graph 
    scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0,0))+
  #removing panel background and border, gridlines,and axis lines and tick marks 
    theme(panel.background =element_blank(), panel.border =  element_blank(),
           panel.grid.major  = element_blank() , panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), axis.ticks.y = element_blank() , axis.line.y = element_blank(),)

comp_df <- df_comp %>%

Financial performance analysis depend on returns; If I buy a stock today for 100 and I sell it tomorrow for 101.75, my one-day return, assuming no transaction costs, is 1.75%. So given the adjusted closing prices, our first step is to calculate daily and monthly returns.

#calculate daily returns
myStocks_returns_daily <- myStocks %>%
  tq_transmute(select     = adjusted, 
               mutate_fun = periodReturn, 
               period     = "daily", 
               type       = "log",
               col_rename = "daily_returns",
               cols = c(nested.col))  

#calculate monthly  returns
myStocks_returns_monthly <- myStocks %>%
  tq_transmute(select     = adjusted, 
               mutate_fun = periodReturn, 
               period     = "monthly", 
               type       = "arithmetic",
               col_rename = "monthly_returns",
               cols = c(nested.col)) 

#calculate yearly returns
myStocks_returns_annual <- myStocks %>%
  group_by(symbol) %>%
  tq_transmute(select     = adjusted, 
               mutate_fun = periodReturn, 
               period     = "yearly", 
               type       = "arithmetic",
               col_rename = "yearly_returns",
               cols = c(nested.col))

Create a table where you summarise monthly returns for each of the stocks and SPY; min, max, median, mean, SD.

#creating sum_month for summary statistics for each stock
sum_month <- myStocks_returns_monthly %>%
  group_by(symbol)%>%
  summarize(
            min = round(min(monthly_returns),2),
            max = round(max(monthly_returns),2),
            median = round(median(monthly_returns),2),
            mean = round(mean(monthly_returns),2) ,
            SD = round(sd(monthly_returns),2)) %>%
  rename(., c("Symbol" = "symbol" , 'Min' = 'min' , 'Max' = 'max' , 'Median' = 'median' , 'Mean' = 'mean'))

TYPE YOUR ANSWER AFTER (AND OUTSIDE!) THIS BLOCKQUOTE.

The data above illustrates the distribution of monthly returns of 5 stocks, in addition to the SPX, over a period of approximately 10 years.

We understand that risk is a function of implied volatility and price-deviation from expected returns. Our analysis on the data above suggests that stocks with fatter tails represent higher volatility, and hence have a higher risk profile.

Using this Criteria, we can ascertain that SNAPCHAT(SNAP) and Pinterest(PINS) fall on the riskier spectrum of stocks. However we also note that risk aversion has a profound impact on an investor’s perception and different investment strategies (Long / Short) can yield returns in market upside & downside. In our opinion, SPDR S&P 500 (SPY) represents the least risk owing to thinner tails and higher peak. From an illustrative perspective, we can note that the probability of achieving a positive return is higher than 50% on the SPY ticker, as suggested by a higher area under the curve.Hence, this leads us to believe that the SPX is a less risky stock and offers more exposure to the upside.

Finally, make a plot that shows the expected monthly return (mean) of a stock on the Y axis and the risk (standard deviation) in the X-axis. Please use ggrepel::geom_text_repel() to label each stock

# creating df for mean and sd
 
meanSD_df <- myStocks_returns_monthly %>%
  group_by(symbol)%>%
  summarize(
            mean = round(mean(monthly_returns),4) ,
            SD = round(sd(monthly_returns),4)) %>%
  rename('Mean' = 'mean')
  
  

# plotting the graph 
ggplot(meanSD_df , aes(x = SD , y = Mean , label = symbol ,)) + 
  geom_point(shape = 21 , aes(fill = symbol) , size = 4) +
  geom_text_repel(nudge_x = 0.01)+
  theme_economist()+
  scale_fill_solarized()+
  labs(title= 'Scatter plot of Mean vs SD', x = 'Standard Deviation' , y = 'Mean' , fill = 'Symbol') +
  
  # removing panel background and border, gridlines,and axis lines and tick marks 
  theme(panel.background =element_blank(), 
      panel.border =  element_blank(),
      panel.grid.major  = element_blank() , 
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
      axis.ticks.y = element_blank() , 
      axis.line.y = element_line(), 
      legend.position = "right" , 
      legend.background = element_blank(),
      legend.key = element_blank(),
      axis.title = element_text(face = 'bold'),
      plot.title = element_text(face = 'bold')) +
  
  # adding linear regression 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE , colour = 'black' , size = .1 ,linetype  = 'dotted')

What can you infer from this plot? Are there any stocks which, while being riskier, do not have a higher expected return?

TYPE YOUR ANSWER AFTER (AND OUTSIDE!) THIS BLOCKQUOTE.

The above graph represents the mean vs the standard deviation for the various stocks. In addition to the above, a regression has been performed to ascertain the risk-return profile of the selected stocks. The regression represents the linear relationship between the expected return and the standard deviation, for illustrative purposes.

The criteria established is that Stocks which fall below the line represent lower returns than what would be expected given their level of risk.Snapchat(SNAP), based on the criteria, has lower return for a given level of risk,when juxtaposed to Pinterest (PINS), which offers a higher rate of return for a broadly similar level of risk.

We further investigate the average number of years an employee stays at any company, which is calculated by the sum of total working years of all employees divided by the total number of companies worked for of all employees.

# Calculate total working year for all stuff

  summarise(sum(total_working_years))

  summarise(sum(num_companies_worked))

leave_fre <- sum_work_year/sum_num_company
leave_fre %>%

As seen above, the average number of years at any 1 company is 4.19 years, which is lower than the average years at IBM. We can therefore argue that IBM appears to be a more desirable workplace than the average company which the employees have worked in.

6 Challenge 2: 2016 California Contributors plots

As discussed in class, I would like you to reproduce the plot that shows the top ten cities in highest amounts raised in political contributions in California during the 2016 US Presidential election.

To get this plot, you must join two dataframes; the one you have with all contributions, and data that can translate zipcodes to cities. You can find a file with all US zipcodes, e.g., here http://www.uszipcodelist.com/download.html.

The easiest way would be to create two plots and then place one next to each other. For this, you will need the patchwork package. https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/patchwork/index.html

While this is ok, what if one asked you to create the same plot for the top 10 candidates and not just the top two? The most challenging part is how to reorder within categories, and for this you will find Julia Silge’s post on REORDERING AND FACETTING FOR GGPLOT2 useful.

# Make sure you use vroom() as it is significantly faster than read.csv()
library(patchwork)
library(tidytext)

# reading data for Trump and Hillary
CA_contributors_2016 <- vroom::vroom(here::here("data","CA_contributors_2016.csv")) %>% filter(cand_nm=="Clinton, Hillary Rodham"|cand_nm=="Trump, Donald J.")
zipcodes <- vroom::vroom(here::here("data","zip_code_database.csv"))[,1:3]

#join by zipcode
together <- merge(CA_contributors_2016,zipcodes,by.x ="zip",by.y = "zip")

# getting top 10 cities contributed
cleaned <- together %>% group_by(cand_nm,primary_city) %>% 
  summarise(total_cont=sum(contb_receipt_amt))  %>% 
  ungroup %>% 
  group_by(cand_nm) %>% 
  top_n(10,total_cont)

# plotting ordered bar graphs
ggplot(cleaned, aes(reorder_within(primary_city, total_cont, cand_nm),total_cont,fill=cand_nm)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE)+
  facet_wrap(~cand_nm,scales="free") +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_x_reordered() + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::dollar_format()) +
  labs(
    title ="Where did candidates raise most money?",
    y     ="Amount raised"
  )

Check minus (1/5): Displays minimal effort. Doesn’t complete all components. Code is poorly written and not documented. Uses the same type of plot for each graph, or doesn’t use plots appropriate for the variables being analyzed.

Check (3/5): Solid effort. Hits all the elements. No clear mistakes. Easy to follow (both the code and the output).

Check plus (5/5): Finished all components of the assignment correctly and addressed both challenges. Code is well-documented (both self-documented and with additional comments as necessary). Used tidyverse, instead of base R. Graphs and tables are properly labelled. Analysis is clear and easy to follow, either because graphs are labeled clearly or you’ve written additional text to describe how you interpret the output.
